1
00:00:00,980 --> 00:00:06,970
Liftoff is usually the most environmentally harmful stage of any space mission

2
00:00:07,070 --> 00:00:11,040
with vast quantities of fuel burnt up in a matter of minutes

3
00:00:11,090 --> 00:00:12,280
For instance

4
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:18,050
SpaceX's Falcon 9 gets through 112 tons of refined fuel

5
00:00:18,410 --> 00:00:21,980
emitting about 336 tons of Co 2

6
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:28,750
This is the equivalent produced by your average car driving almost 70 times around the world

7
00:00:29,380 --> 00:00:31,120
As well as greenhouse gases

8
00:00:31,130 --> 00:00:34,580
rocket engines emit particles that destroy ozone

9
00:00:35,310 --> 00:00:40,270
These issues are growing more pressing with the emergence of commercial space flight

10
00:00:40,510 --> 00:00:44,660
There were 114 space launches in 2020

11
00:00:44,710 --> 00:00:48,680
but there may be up to 1000 per year in future

12
00:00:49,490 --> 00:00:55,130
Sustainable fuels are the top priority to enable greener space travel

13
00:00:55,390 --> 00:00:58,650
Current spacecraft use a variety of fuels

14
00:00:58,690 --> 00:01:01,520
but most are based on fossil fuels

15
00:01:01,830 --> 00:01:06,440
One potentially greener option is liquid hydrogen and oxygen

16
00:01:06,770 --> 00:01:14,610
Hydrogen can be obtained sustainably by using solar power to break water down into oxygen and hydrogen

17
00:01:15,460 --> 00:01:21,000
Reusable rockets can cut down on some of the waste associated with spaceflight

18
00:01:21,220 --> 00:01:23,090
Traditionallyboosters

19
00:01:23,100 --> 00:01:23,870
fuel tanks

20
00:01:23,870 --> 00:01:27,160
and other components are treated as as expendable

21
00:01:27,510 --> 00:01:32,800
but guiding them back to Earth in a controlled manner opens new possibilities

22
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:38,660
Most components from the Falcon 9 can be reused up to 100 times

23
